ARIMA - Time series analysis on 'Microsoft' stock data(MSFT)¶

Team: Hieu Nguyen, Nithya Devadoss, Ramesh Simhambhatla, Ramya Mandava¶

Date: 10/21/2018¶

Abstract¶

In time series analysis, an autoregressive integrated moving average (ARIMA) model is a generalization of an autoregressive moving average (ARMA) model. Both of these models are fitted to time series data either to better understand the data or to predict future points in the series (forecasting). Since stationarity is an assumption underlying many statistical procedures used in time series analysis, non-stationary data is often transformed to become stationary.A stationary time series is one whose statistical properties such as mean, variance, autocorrelation, etc. are all constant over time. In this case study, we will acquire stock data for Microsoft Corporation (Stock symbol: MSFT), transform the data to stationary and conduct tests to determine most appropriate ARIMA model.

Introduction¶

We acquire Microsoft Corporation (MSFT) stock closing data . We have limited the data from January 2014 to September 2018. The Investors Exchange (IEX) provides this data through an API available in Python "pandas_datareader" package. Our objective is to investigate the time series data is stationary and test using a ARIMA model. We would test ARIMA using our intuition with ACF and PACF, and then a grid search (brute force) technique is used to determine the best p, q and d values that yield the least Root Mean Squared Error.

ACF: We can calculate the correlation for time series observations with observations with previous time steps, called lags. Because the correlation of the time series observations is calculated with values of the same series at previous times, this is called a serial correlation, or an autocorrelation. The Pearsons correlation coefficient is a number between -1 and 1 that describes a negative or positive correlation respectively. A value of zero indicates no correlation.

A partial autocorrelation is a summary of the relationship between an observation in a time series with observations at prior time steps with the relationships of intervening observations removed. It contrasts with the autocorrelation function, which does not control for other lags.

Analysis of plot¶

Reviewing the plot above, there seems to be a trend in the plot and time series with trends, or with seasonality, are not stationary the trend and seasonality will affect the value of the time series at different times. On the other hand, a white noise series is stationary it does not matter when you observe it, it should look much the same at any point in time.

Dicky-Fuller test is popular for checking the seasonality in a given time series data.Statsmodels library provides tools to implement Dicky-Fuller test and to plot other related tests.

The test_stationarity() function displays the results of Dickey-Fuller test along with the rolling mean and standard deviation.

from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
def test_stationarity(timeseries):
    
    #Determing rolling statistics
    rolmean = timeseries.rolling(12).mean()
    rolstd = timeseries.rolling(12).std()

    #Plot rolling statistics:
    orig = plt.plot(timeseries, color='blue',label='Original')
    mean = plt.plot(rolmean, color='red', label='Rolling Mean')
    std = plt.plot(rolstd, color='black', label = 'Rolling Std')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.title('Rolling Mean & Standard Deviation')
    plt.show(block=False)
    
    #Perform Dickey-Fuller test:
    print('Results of Dickey-Fuller Test:')
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries, autolag='AIC')
    dfoutput = pd.Series(dftest[0:4], index=['Test Statistic','p-value','#Lags Used','Number of Observations Used'])
    for key,value in dftest[4].items():
        dfoutput['Critical Value (%s)'%key] = value
    print(round(dfoutput, 3))

Statistical tests make strong assumptions about the data. They can only be used to inform the degree to which a null hypothesis can be rejected or fail to be reject. The result must be interpreted for a given problem to be meaningful.

The intuition behind Dickey-Fuller unit root test implemented above is that it determines how strongly a time series is defined by a trend.

The null hypothesis of the test is that the time series can be represented by a unit root, which means it is stationary and time depedant structure. The alternate hypothesis indicates that the time series is stationary.

Results provide a test statistic of 2.318 which is much higher than even the 10% critical value, hence it is evident that the time-series data is non-sationary.

Differencing¶

One way of making data more stationary is by subtracting the trend from our data or in other words-compute the differences between consecutive observations. This is known as differencing.

In [26]:
diff=price-price.shift()
diff.dropna(inplace=True)
diff.plot()
test_stationarity(diff)

Results of Dickey-Fuller Test:
Test Statistic                  -13.195

As can be observed from the results above, a first order differncing yielded a test statistic of -33 which is much lower than the 1% critical value. Therefore, it is sufficient to make the time series data stationary.

Modeling using ARIMA¶

ARIMA is a class of model that captures a suite of different standard temporal structures in time series data.

ARIMA stands for: [1]

AR: Autoregression.

  • Current prediction depends on the past results
  • Similar to a Markov chain, but can be longer than 1 step

I: Integrated.

  • Not only is the past result import, but the DIFFERENCES between the past results are important

MA: Moving Average.

  • The average of previous results is also important.

Each of these components are explicitly specified in the model as a parameter. A standard notation is used of ARIMA(p,d,q) where the parameters are substituted with integer values to quickly indicate the specific ARIMA model being used.

The parameters of the ARIMA model are defined as follows:

  • p: This term represents the lag order which is the number of lag observations included in the model.
  • d: This is the degree of differencing indicating the number of times the raw observations are differenced.
  • q: This is the order of moving average.

It is important to pick the right combinations of p,q and d. The below functions help choose the optimal values for p,q and d.

  • Autocorrelation Function (ACF): The plot summarizes the correlation of an observation with lag values. The x-axis shows the lag and the y-axis shows the correlation coefficient between -1 and 1 for negative and positive correlation.
  • Partial Autocorrelation Function (PACF): The plot summarizes the correlations for an observation with lag values that is not accounted for by prior lagged observations.

Autocorrelation Function(ACF)¶

In [27]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import acf, pacf
import numpy as np
acf_msft_plot = acf(diff, nlags=20)
#Plot ACF: 
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 4))

plt.subplot(121) 
plt.plot(acf_msft_plot)
plt.xticks(np.arange(21))
plt.axhline(y=0,linestyle='--',color='gray')
plt.axhline(y=-1.96/np.sqrt(len(acf_msft_plot)),linestyle='--',color='gray')
plt.axhline(y=1.96/np.sqrt(len(acf_msft_plot)),linestyle='--',color='gray')
for i in range(1,20):
    plt.axvline(x=i,linestyle=':',color='gray')
plt.title('Autocorrelation Function')
Out[27]:
Text(0.5,1,'Autocorrelation Function')

As can be noted from the above graph, the AC plot drops immediately under UCL indicating that the time series is already stationary and no higher order differencing needs to be implemented. This is also supported by teh Dicky-Fuller test performed earlier.

Rule 6: If thepartial autocorrelation function(PACF) of the differenced series displays a sharp cutoff and/or the lag-1 autocorrelation ispositive--i.e., if the series appears slightly "underdifferenced"--then consider adding one or moreARterms to the model. The lag beyond which the PACF cuts off is the indicated number of AR terms.

Rule 6 applies to our PACF curve as it sharply drops to 0 and stays within UCL and LCL. Therefore an AR term needs to be added to the model.(p = 1)

Rule 7: If theautocorrelation function(ACF) of the differenced series displays a sharp cutoff and/or the lag-1 autocorrelation isnegative--i.e., if the series appears slightly "overdifferenced"--then consider adding anMAterm to the model. The lag beyond which the ACF cuts off is the indicated number of MA terms.

Rule 7 is not applicable based on our ACF curve plotted earlier. Therefore we chose to pick to have p=1(one AR term) in our final model.

Fitting ARIMA model¶

As explained above our initial model has p=1, d=0 and q=0.

Parameter Optimization(Brute Force/ Grid Search)¶

Generally the parameters p,d,q are between 0 and 3. Therefore, only 27 runs would be needed to get the best fit. All of them will be checked in a for loop to pick optimal values for p, d and q.

In [31]:
loss_best = 1E16
best_ints = [-1,-1,-1]
for p in range(4):
    for d in range(3):
        for q in range(3):
            model = ARIMA(diff, order=(p, d, q))  
            try:
                results_ARIMA = model.fit(disp=-1)
            except ValueError:
                pass
            except:
                pass
            plt.plot(diff)
            plt.plot(results_ARIMA.fittedvalues, color='red')
            x=pd.DataFrame(results_ARIMA.fittedvalues)
            x=x.join(diff)
            x['out']=(x.iloc[:,0]-x.iloc[:,1])**2
            loss=np.sqrt(x['out'].sum())
            plt.title('RSS: %.4f'% loss)
            if loss < loss_best:
                print(loss)
                loss_best = loss
                best_ints=[p,d,q]
            plt.show()
            print(p,d,q)

Conclusion¶

Even though best_ints showed a [3,0,2] combination, based on Brute Force technique and by observing ACF and PACF curves, it is evident that best fit happened with a [1,0,0] combination of p,d and q values respectively. RSS associated with this combination is very close to loss_best and is at 27.98.
